# @param {Integer[][]} grid
# @return {Integer[][]}
def construct_product_matrix(grid)
    n = grid.length
    m = grid[0].length
    product_matrix = Array.new(n) { Array.new(m, 1) }
    total_product = 1
    zero_count = 0

    # Calculate total product and count zeros
    grid.each do |row|
        row.each do |element|
            unless element.zero?
                total_product = (total_product * element) % 12345
            else
                zero_count += 1
            end
        end
    end

    grid.each_with_index do |row, i|
        row.each_with_index do |element, j|
            if zero_count > 1
                product_matrix[i][j] = 0
            elsif zero_count == 1
                product_matrix[i][j] = element.zero? ? total_product : 0
            else
                # Here, theoretically, we would divide total_product by element and take modulo 12345
                # But direct division is not feasible without additional math operations.
                # This part of the solution may need adjustment to comply with modular arithmetic rules.
                product_matrix[i][j] = (total_product * pow(element, 12343, 12345)) % 12345 if element != 0
            end
        end
    end

    product_matrix
end

# Fast power algorithm to calculate base^exp % mod
def pow(base, exp, mod)
    result = 1
    base = base % mod
    while exp > 0
        result = (result * base) % mod if exp.odd?
        exp = exp >> 1
        base = (base * base) % mod
    end
    result
end
